# Pocket Architect - Testing Examples

## Prerequisites

1. Set up the conda environment:
```bash
# Option 1: Use environment.yml (recommended)
conda env create -f environment.yml
conda activate pocket-architect
pip install -e .

# Option 2: Manual setup
conda create -n pocket-architect python=3.12 -y
conda activate pocket-architect
pip install -e .
```

2. Ensure AWS credentials are configured:
```bash
aws configure
# OR set environment variables:
# export AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=your_key
# export AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=your_secret
```

## Example 1: Deploy a Basic Web Server

Deploy a simple web server using the built-in `basic-web` blueprint:

```bash
pocket-architect deploy basic-web --project test-web-1
```

This will:
- Create a VPC with CIDR 10.1.0.0/16
- Launch a t3.large EC2 instance
- Open ports 22 (SSH) and 8080 (web)
- Allocate an Elastic IP
- Output SSH and web access information

**Expected output:**
- SSH command: `ssh -i ~/.ssh/pa-test-web-1-key.pem ec2-user@<public-ip>`
- Service URL: `http://<public-ip>:8080`

## Example 2: Deploy with Interactive Mode

Deploy with custom parameters:

```bash
pocket-architect deploy basic-web --project test-web-2 --interactive
```

You'll be prompted for:
- Instance type (default: t3.large)
- ACM Certificate ARN (if using ALB)

## Example 3: Deploy Bare Metal Instance

Deploy a minimal instance with just SSH access:

```bash
pocket-architect deploy bare-metal --project test-bare-1
```

This creates:
- t3.medium instance
- Only port 22 open
- Elastic IP for access

## Example 4: List All Projects

Check what projects are deployed:

```bash
pocket-architect list
```

Shows a table with:
- Project name
- Blueprint used
- Creation date
- Current status (Running, Stopped, etc.)

## Example 5: Create a Snapshot

After setting up your instance, create a snapshot:

```bash
# First, SSH into your instance and set it up
ssh -i ~/.ssh/pa-test-web-1-key.pem ec2-user@<public-ip>

# Install nginx or your app, configure it, etc.
# Then exit and create snapshot:

pocket-architect snapshot create test-web-1 --name nginx-ready --note "Nginx installed and configured"
```

This will:
- Create an EBS snapshot of the root volume
- Create an AMI from the snapshot
- Save metadata for later use
- Take a few minutes to complete

## Example 6: List Snapshots

View all saved snapshots:

```bash
pocket-architect snapshot list
```

Shows:
- Snapshot name
- Snapshot ID
- Source project
- AMI ID (for deployment)
- Creation date
- Notes

## Example 7: Deploy from Snapshot

Deploy a new project using a saved snapshot:

```bash
pocket-architect deploy basic-web --project test-web-3 --snapshot nginx-ready
```

This will:
- Find the snapshot and its cached AMI
- Launch a new instance from that AMI
- Your previous configuration will be preserved

## Example 8: Create Custom Blueprint

Create your own blueprint interactively:

```bash
pocket-architect blueprint create
```

Follow the prompts:
- Blueprint name: `my-app`
- Instance type: `t3.small`
- Ports: `22,3000`
- Use ALB? `no`
- Use Elastic IP? `yes`
- User data? (optional)

The blueprint will be saved to `~/.pocket-architect/templates/my-app.yaml`

## Example 9: List Blueprints

See all available blueprints:

```bash
pocket-architect blueprint list
```

Shows built-in and user-created blueprints.

## Example 10: Deploy Custom Blueprint

Use your custom blueprint:

```bash
pocket-architect deploy my-app --project test-custom-1
```

## Example 11: Stop a Project (Pause Without Deleting)

Stop a project's instance to save compute costs while keeping everything:

```bash
pocket-architect stop test-web-1
```

This will:
- Stop the EC2 instance (saves compute costs)
- Keep all resources (VPC, subnet, security groups, Elastic IP, etc.)
- Keep project state and resource tracking
- **Note**: You still pay for EBS storage and Elastic IP while stopped

## Example 12: Start a Stopped Project

Restart a stopped project:

```bash
pocket-architect start test-web-1
```

This will:
- Start the stopped EC2 instance
- Wait for it to be running
- Show SSH and access information

## Example 13: Tear Down a Project

Remove a project and all its resources:

```bash
pocket-architect teardown test-web-1
```

You'll be prompted for confirmation. To skip confirmation:

```bash
pocket-architect teardown test-web-1 --force
```

This deletes:
- EC2 instance
- Elastic IP (if used)
- ALB and target groups (if used)
- Security groups
- Subnets
- VPC and internet gateway
- Key pair (AWS and local .pem file)
- Project state

## Example 14: Delete a Snapshot

Remove a snapshot and its AMI:

```bash
pocket-architect snapshot delete nginx-ready
```

This will:
- Deregister the AMI
- Delete the EBS snapshot
- Remove from snapshot index

## Example 15: Full Workflow

Complete workflow from deployment to snapshot to redeploy:

```bash
# 1. Deploy initial project
pocket-architect deploy basic-web --project my-app

# 2. SSH in and set it up
ssh -i ~/.ssh/pa-my-app-key.pem ec2-user@<public-ip>
# ... install software, configure ...

# 3. Create snapshot
pocket-architect snapshot create my-app --name v1-stable

# 4. Tear down original
pocket-architect teardown my-app --force

# 5. Deploy from snapshot later
pocket-architect deploy basic-web --project my-app-v2 --snapshot v1-stable

# 6. Clean up when done
pocket-architect teardown my-app-v2 --force
pocket-architect snapshot delete v1-stable
```

## Example 16: Using ALB with Certificate

If you have an ACM certificate ARN, deploy with ALB:

```bash
# Get your certificate ARN first
aws acm list-certificates --region us-east-1

# Deploy with ALB (requires certificate ARN in interactive mode)
pocket-architect deploy basic-web --project web-with-alb --interactive
# When prompted, provide your certificate ARN
```

Or create a custom blueprint with ALB configured.

## Example 17: Stop/Start Workflow

Pause and resume projects to save costs:

```bash
# Deploy a project
pocket-architect deploy basic-web --project my-app

# Work on it, set it up...

# Stop it when not in use (saves compute costs)
pocket-architect stop my-app

# Later, start it again
pocket-architect start my-app

# When done, tear it down completely
pocket-architect teardown my-app --force
```

**Cost savings:**
- Stopped instance: No compute charges, but you pay for:
  - EBS storage (~$0.10/GB/month)
  - Elastic IP (~$0.005/hour if not attached to running instance)
  - ALB (if used, ~$0.0225/hour even when idle)

**When to use stop vs teardown:**
- Use `stop` when you'll resume work soon
- Use `teardown` when you're completely done

## Example 18: Verbose Logging

See detailed AWS API calls:

```bash
pocket-architect deploy basic-web --project debug-test --verbose
```

## ML Architecture Examples

### Example 19: Deploy GPU Training Instance

Deploy a GPU instance for ML model training with Jupyter Lab:

```bash
pocket-architect deploy ml-training-gpu --project my-ml-training
```

This will:
- Create a g4dn.xlarge instance (NVIDIA T4 GPU)
- Auto-detect and use the latest Deep Learning AMI
- Install PyTorch, TensorFlow, Jupyter Lab
- Open ports 22 (SSH) and 8888 (Jupyter)
- Allocate an Elastic IP

**Expected output:**
- SSH command: `ssh -i ~/.ssh/pa-my-ml-training-key.pem ec2-user@<public-ip>`
- Jupyter Lab: `http://<public-ip>:8888`

**Note:** GPU instances may not be available in all regions. Check availability with:
```bash
aws ec2 describe-instance-type-offerings --location-type region --filters "Name=instance-type,Values=g4dn.xlarge"
```

### Example 20: Deploy Multi-GPU Training Instance

Deploy a multi-GPU instance for distributed training:

```bash
pocket-architect deploy ml-training-multi-gpu --project distributed-training
```

This creates:
- g4dn.4xlarge instance (4x NVIDIA T4 GPUs)
- Same ML stack as single GPU instance
- Ready for distributed training with PyTorch DDP or TensorFlow MirroredStrategy

**Cost note:** Multi-GPU instances are significantly more expensive (~$1.20/hour for g4dn.4xlarge). Use `stop` when not training.

### Example 21: Deploy Model Serving API

Deploy a model serving endpoint with ALB:

```bash
pocket-architect deploy ml-serving-api --project model-api
```

This will:
- Create a t3.large instance
- Install FastAPI and model serving framework
- Create an ALB for load balancing
- Open ports 22 (SSH) and 8000 (API)
- API accessible via ALB DNS name

**Expected output:**
- ALB URL: `http://<alb-dns-name>`
- Health check: `http://<alb-dns-name>/health`
- API endpoint: `http://<alb-dns-name>/predict`

**Next steps:**
1. SSH into the instance
2. Edit `~/model-serving/app.py` to load your model
3. Restart the service: `sudo systemctl restart ml-serving`

### Example 22: Deploy Jupyter Notebook Server

Deploy a CPU-based Jupyter Lab server for experimentation:

```bash
pocket-architect deploy ml-jupyter-server --project my-notebooks
```

This creates:
- t3.large instance (CPU-optimized)
- Jupyter Lab pre-installed and configured
- Accessible on port 8888

**Access:**
- Jupyter Lab: `http://<public-ip>:8888`
- No password required (configured for development use)

**Security note:** For production, modify the user_data script to add authentication.

### Example 23: Deploy MLflow Tracking Server

Deploy an MLflow server for experiment tracking:

```bash
pocket-architect deploy ml-mlflow-server --project mlflow-tracking
```

This will:
- Create a t3.medium instance
- Install and configure MLflow server
- Open ports 22 (SSH) and 5000 (MLflow UI)
- Start MLflow server automatically

**Expected output:**
- MLflow UI: `http://<public-ip>:5000`
- Backend store: Local file system (`~/mlflow/mlruns`)
- Artifact store: S3 (configure bucket in service file)

**Configuration:**
1. SSH into instance
2. Edit `/etc/systemd/system/mlflow.service` to set your S3 bucket
3. Restart: `sudo systemctl restart mlflow`

**Using MLflow:**
```python
import mlflow
mlflow.set_tracking_uri("http://<public-ip>:5000")
mlflow.set_experiment("my-experiment")
# Your training code here
```

### Example 24: Deploy Complete ML Pipeline

Deploy a full ML environment with training, tracking, and serving:

```bash
pocket-architect deploy ml-pipeline-full --project complete-ml-stack
```

This creates:
- g4dn.xlarge GPU instance
- Jupyter Lab (port 8888)
- MLflow server (port 5000)
- Full ML frameworks (PyTorch, TensorFlow)
- Serving framework (FastAPI)

**Access points:**
- Jupyter Lab: `http://<public-ip>:8888`
- MLflow UI: `http://<public-ip>:5000`
- SSH: `ssh -i ~/.ssh/pa-complete-ml-stack-key.pem ec2-user@<public-ip>`

**Workflow:**
1. Use Jupyter Lab to develop and train models
2. Log experiments to MLflow
3. Export trained models for serving
4. Deploy models using the serving framework

### Example 25: ML Training Workflow with Snapshots

Complete ML training workflow with snapshot management:

```bash
# 1. Deploy GPU training instance
pocket-architect deploy ml-training-gpu --project training-v1

# 2. SSH in and train your model
ssh -i ~/.ssh/pa-training-v1-key.pem ec2-user@<public-ip>
# ... train model, save checkpoints ...

# 3. Create snapshot with trained model
pocket-architect snapshot create training-v1 --name model-v1-trained --note "ResNet50 trained on custom dataset"

# 4. Stop instance to save costs
pocket-architect stop training-v1

# 5. Later, deploy from snapshot for inference
pocket-architect deploy ml-serving-api --project inference-api --snapshot model-v1-trained
```

### Example 26: Cost Optimization for ML Training

Save costs by stopping GPU instances when not in use:

```bash
# Deploy training instance
pocket-architect deploy ml-training-gpu --project training

# Train your model...
# When done training, stop the instance
pocket-architect stop training

# Later, resume training
pocket-architect start training

# When completely done, tear down
pocket-architect teardown training --force
```

**Cost comparison:**
- g4dn.xlarge running: ~$0.50/hour
- g4dn.xlarge stopped: ~$0.10/hour (EBS storage only)
- Savings: ~80% when stopped

### Example 27: Multi-Instance ML Setup

Deploy separate instances for different ML tasks:

```bash
# Training instance
pocket-architect deploy ml-training-gpu --project ml-training

# Tracking server
pocket-architect deploy ml-mlflow-server --project mlflow

# Serving endpoint
pocket-architect deploy ml-serving-api --project ml-api
```

This setup allows:
- Independent scaling of each component
- Training on GPU, serving on CPU (cost optimization)
- Centralized experiment tracking

**Connect them:**
- Point training instance to MLflow server: `mlflow.set_tracking_uri("http://<mlflow-ip>:5000")`
- Deploy models from training to serving instance

## Troubleshooting

### Check AWS Identity
Every command verifies your AWS credentials and shows:
```
You are operating as: arn:aws:iam::123456789012:user/yourname
All resources will be created in this account: 123456789012
```

### View Project State
Project state is stored in:
```
~/.pocket-architect/projects/<project-name>/state.json
```

### View Snapshots Index
```
~/.pocket-architect/snapshots.json
```

### Common Issues

1. **"AWS credentials not configured"**
   - Run `aws configure` or set environment variables

2. **"Project already exists"**
   - Tear down the existing project first, or use a different name

3. **"Snapshot not found"**
   - List snapshots to see available names/IDs
   - Use exact name or snapshot ID

4. **Instance not accessible**
   - Check security group rules
   - Verify Elastic IP is associated
   - Check instance status: `aws ec2 describe-instances`

